Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Pop the @diced butternut squash{300%g} onto a #baking tray{} and sprinkle over half of the @ground cumin{2%tsp}, add a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat the squash well, then arrange in a single layer. Pop on the top shelf of the oven and cook for ~{25-30%mins}, until tender and golden. Turn halfway through cooking.

Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with a pinch of @salt{pinch}, for the rice. When boiling, stir in the @brown basmati rice{150%g} and half the @vegetable stock powder{1/2%tsp}. Bring to the boil again and cook for ~{25%minutes}. TIP: Add more water if it starts to evaporate too much. When cooked, drain the rice thoroughly in a #sieve{} and return to the saucepan, off the heat. Cover with a #lid{} to keep warm.

While the rice cooks, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped) into small pieces. Peel and grate the @ginger{1/2%tsp}(peeled and grated). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated, or use a garlic press). Roughly chop the @coriander{1%bunch}(roughly chopped, stalks and leaves separated). Halve the @green chilli{1/2}(halved, deseeded and finely chopped) lengthways, deseed then finely chop. Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1/2%400g can} in a sieve.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium heat. Once hot, add the onion, cook until soft, stirring occasionally, ~{3-4%mins}. Stir in the ginger, garlic, @ground turmeric{2%tsp}, @North Indian style spice mix{1%tsp}, remaining cumin and as much chilli as you dare. Cook for ~{1%minute}. Stir in the chickpeas to coat in the mixture, then add the @light coconut milk{200%ml}, @water{150%ml} and remaining @vegetable stock powder{1/2%tsp} to the pan.

Bring the curry to the boil then reduce the heat and cover with a lid. Simmer until thick and creamy, stirring occasionally, ~{8-12%mins}. When cooked, stir in the @baby spinach{125%g} one handful at a time and gently stir until wilted.

Once everything is ready, stir the roasted squash and half the coriander through the curry and season to taste with salt and pepper if needed. Stir the @nigella seeds{1/2%tsp} through the rice. Serve the rice and curry in #bowls{}. Sprinkle over the remaining coriander. Enjoy!

> We love a good Butternut & Chickpea Curry and this deliciously simple, chef-curated recipe doesn't disappoint. Time to bust out the pots and pans!